  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN151.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">ta[laimakaṉ piriviṉkaṇ vēṟupaṭṭa talaimaka]ḷ collitu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What SHE said who was had undergone changes during the separation from HIM.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN151.2">
            <lg type="edition">
              <l>taṇṇayan tuṟaivōrt tāṅkit tāṉayan</l>
              <l>kiṉṉamar kēḷirō ṭēmuṟak keḻīi</l>
              <l>nakuta lāṟṟār nalkūrn tōreṉa</l>
              <l>mikuporu ḷiṉaiyu neñcamō ṭaruḷpiṟi</l>
              <l>tāmmaṉ vāḻi tōḻi kālviri</l>
              <l>puṟuvaḷi yeṟitoṟuṅ kalaṅkip poṟivarik</l>
              <l>kalaimāṉ ṟalaiyiṉ mutaṉmutaṟ kavartta</l>
              <l>kōṭalaṅ kavaṭṭa kuṟuṅkā luḻuñciṟ</l>
              <l>ṟāṟutiṉai viḷainta neṟṟa māṭumaka</l>
              <l>ḷariṟkōṟ paṟaiyi ṉaiyeṉa volikkum</l>
              <l>patukkait tāya cetukkai nīḻaṟ</l>
              <l>kaḷḷi muḷḷaraip poruntic cellunark</l>
              <l>kuṟuvatu kūṟuñ ciṟucen nāviṉ</l>
              <l>maṇipeyart taṉṉa teṇkuraṟ</l>
              <l>kaṇivāyp palliya kāṭiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>He who keeps loving them, enduring, saying</l>
                <l>“[even though] loving, those who are poor cannot smile,</l>
                <l>united to have pleasure with [their] kin whose beuaty is pleasing!”, (1-3)</l>
                <l>his consideration becomes something different, oh friend,</l>
                <l>along with his heart that is very desperate for wealth, as time goes by, (4f.)</l>
                <l>– he who has gone to traverse the wilderness of geckos with the mouths of astrologers, (15)</l>
                <l>with clear voices, as if bells were rung, (14)</l>
                <l>with little red tongues that talk of what will befall (13)</l>
                <l>those who go [there], staying on the thorny trunks of the spurges (12)</l>
                <l>in the blunted shade spread by the stone heaps, (11)</l>
                <l>where, wonderfully like the drums of the dancing girls with interlacing sticks</l>
                <l>the seed pods ripened between the grasses in bunches sound (9f.)</l>
                <l>on the short-trunked Sirissa with bending pretty forked branches (8)</l>
                <l>that branch off on every base, like the [antlers on] the head of the stag of the spotted deer, (7)</l>
                <l>stirred up whenever the moving wind beats [against them]. (6)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
